    "narrative": "Our offensive engine today centers on the elite scoring trio of **Austin Riley**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **James Wood**, all of whom surpass the 70-point threshold. **Austin Riley** is the clear anchor at 72.43, benefiting from a highly favorable matchup against Jake Irvin (xERA 4.92) and a prime cleanup spot. **James Wood** follows closely at 71.27; his role as the table-setter out of the leadoff spot against Bryce Elder is a massive boost to his floor, while **Tyler Soderstrom** leverages the same exploitable matchup against Hancock to provide excellent power upside from the OF1 slot. These three are the pillars of today's efficiency strategy, effectively negating the lower projections elsewhere in the order.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the card was keeping **Kyle Karros** on the bench at 44.69. While he offers some intrigue against the lefty Wrobleski and carries a slight boost due to a favorable park environment, he fell just short of the efficiency required to crack the starting nine. The optimizer prioritized the higher-ceiling matchups found in **Josh Naylor** and **Max Muncy**, despite their tougher direct SP matchups. We are proceeding with caution regarding **Dalton Rushing**, whose efficiency sits at a marginal 54.28; while the park factors and opposing SP skill help, batting in the nine-hole combined with a tough lefty-on-lefty platoon disadvantage makes him a candidate to be swapped if our deeper bench options\u2014should they enter the game\u2014show better situational leverage. With **Corbin Carroll**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Mickey Moniak** all unavailable due to scheduled off-days or confirmed benching, our remaining roster depth, including **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Seiya Suzuki**, **Brice Turang**, **Gabriel Moreno**, **Luis Campusano**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Alex Freeland**, **Carson Williams**, and **Travis Bazzana**, remains on high alert for pinch-hit opportunities to protect our game caps.",
